December 3rd

2FA Day

Enable 2-Factor Authentication everywhere you can.

  • Download and install Google Authenticator for Android or iOS.
  • Enable 2FA via Google Authenticator on your accounts: Coinbase, Gemini, Kraken, Binance, Google, Facebook, Twitter, Dropbox, iCloud, Amazon/AWS, web hosts and any other site you use.

Note: Avoid SMS 2FA and Authy whenever you can. It is common that phone numbers are stolen in order to gain access to your accounts & crypto. If you must use Authy, turn multi-device support off.

Beast Mode

  • Get a YubiKey or Google Titan hardware key.
  • Use it to super-secure your accounts: Google, Github, Gitlab, Twitter, Facebook, Dropbox, LastPass, Coinbase & AWS.

December 5th

Change your passwords!

Lets face it. Many tout the importance of security, but few follow through and change their passwords at proper intervals. Maybe you even have a few passwords that havent been changed in years. Time to fix that! Here are a few helpful pointers:

  • Use NEW passwords - dont recycle.
  • Use unique, secure passwords that are 8+ characters and use a variety of uppercase letters, lowercase letters, numbers, and symbols.
  • LastPass & 1Password have fun wizardsSecurity Challenge and Watchtower, respectivelythat will help you monitor accounts that have been found in data breaches and even change some passwords for you automagically! After you have added accounts (as you change the passwords), we strongly recommend following up with this wizard.

This tip brought
to you by Ledger!

December 6th

Protect your Personal Information

When signing up for services or creating accounts and entering your personal information, always ask yourself why this information is necessary, how can the applications leverage it, and what would happen if it was 'leaked'?

Does that social media site really need your birthday and hometown? Try to look for tools and services that do not require you to divulge unnecessary Personally Identifiable Information (also known as PII).

Read more tips here.

This tip brought
to you by Status!

December 7th

Log out of old, active sessions

Anytime you log in to a service, you create an 'active session.' For convenience, it keeps you logged even when you close the app or close your browser. If you don't remove old active sessions, it increases the chance of someone maliciously accessing your account.

Additionally, if you use your Google, Twitter, or Facebook account as the 'log in' for another service, if someone hacks your Google account, they can log in to the connected accounts as well. These services also have access to your information via Google or Twitter, if you don't use their service anymore.

Take the time to remove old, active sessions and connected accounts. You can always log in again if you need to.

  • Remove Twitter Connections: Go to Twitter -> Settings and Privacy -> Account -> Apps and Sessions.
  • Remove Google connections.
  • Remove other social media connections.

This tip brought
to you by Dune Analytics!

December 8th

Secure your Telegram account

When you create a Telegram you don't create a username, provide an email address, or create a password.

Unless you've adjusted your Telegram settings, the only thing you need to log in is a code sent to your Telegram or a code sent via SMS. Lets fix that.

  • Enable Local Passcode: 'Settings' > 'Privacy and Security.' Add a PIN under 'passcode lock.'
  • Disable Discovery: Navigate to Settings > Privacy and Security > Phone Number and select Nobody.
  • Deactivate phone calls: Choose Nobody under Settings > Privacy and Security > Phone Calls. Add exceptions for people you trust and do want to be able to call you.
  • Lastly, Enable 2-Step Verification.

This tip brought
to you by Etherscan!

December 9th

Cover your webcam!

Cameras are windows into the world, and webcams are a window into your personal world. Theyre also easily accessed by a hacker that knows what theyre doing. Its a best practice to cover your webcam when youre not using it.

If youve got an external webcam, you can simply unplug it when not in use. Otherwise...

  • Cover it with a webcam cover, which are very cheap and oftentimes given out as promotional items at events.
  • Slide the webcam cover closed if you have a built in cover.
  • If you rarely or never use your webcam, you can simply put a piece of non-transparent tape over it and forget about it altogether.

Webcam covers arent just for webcams! In addition to covering up your desktop/laptop webcam, you can cover up your phone cameras and home devices too, like the Amazon Echo, Google Home Hub, and Facebooks Portal.

December 10th

Have I Been Pwned?

HaveIBeenPwned.com (HIBP) is a site that tracks major data breaches and informs users if their accounts have been compromised. Its likely that at some point youve been breached, so we recommend the following:

  • Look yourself up on haveibeenpwned.com.
  • For any accounts that have been pwned, ensure that you are not using the same password.
  • Change specifically that password.
  • If other data is breached (e.g., address, phone number, or security questions), ensure that data doesnt give anyone else access to an account (e.g., dont protect your online banking with a security question that was revealed during the Adobe breach).
  • Consider creating a new general-purpose email address to disconnect yourself from the past breaches.
December 11th

Create A Crypto Browser Profile

Browser profiles are under-utilized. Oftentimes people stick with one profile, but there are benefits if you use this feature creatively.

A browser profile can store a lot of things that can be used against you. It can store your bookmarks, your saved passwords, your extensions, your security settings, and more.

To enhance your online security and privacy, and reduce risk, you should consider creating a new profile that you only use when youre navigating the world of blockchain. This will keep your crypto extensions/settings/etc. behind an extra layer of protection.

This tip brought
to you by CoinGecko!

December 14th

Don't let the SIM Swappers Win

Your phone number protects a lot of your online accounts. You can use a text message as a 2FA method and to recover your accounts.

Unfortunately, this means that if someone steals your number, aka 'SIM Swapping' you could have you accounts taken over, crypto stolen, and more.

  • Call your cell phone provider and ask them to put an extra PIN on your account.
  • Request that no changes can be made to the account in-person with a government-issued ID.
  • Use a new Google Voice number for SMS 2FA. Make sure this Google voice number is under a very secure Google account.
  • Secure your email! If an attacker can get into your email, they can reset a lot of your passwords.
  • Use 2FA ALWAYS. Google Authenticator is great.

Check out our comprehensive guide on what you can do before, during, and after a SIM swap.

December 17th

Lock Down Your Google Accounts

For many people, their Google accounts are a single point of failure. This means you CANNOT allow any of them to be compromised. You need to lock. them. down.

  • Go to https://myaccount.google.com/security.
  • Click 2-Step Verification
  • Set up a security key (Yubikey), authenticator app (Google Authenticator) and backup codes.
  • Print out the backup codes. Don't store them on a connected device.
  • While still on the 2-Step Verification page, scroll to the bottom under Devices that do not need a second step. Click Revoke all.
  • Return to https://myaccount.google.com/security.
  • Do not turn on Recovery email. If there is a recovery email there, remove it.
  • Do not turn on Recovery phone. If there is a recovery phone number there, remove it.
  • Under Recently used devices remove anything that isnt your primary phone and computer.
  • Review Apps with access to your account. Remove anything you arent actively using.

to you by MetaMask!
